  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Assuming the entire wall is divided into two equal sections—one of length 947 for Matilda and another of length 947 for Ellie—what fraction of the whole wall is painted red if Matilda paints half of her section red and Ellie paints one third of her section red?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Since the wall is divided into two equal sections, each is 947 units long, making the total length of the wall 947 + 947 = 1894 units.\\n2. Matilda paints half of her section: (1/2)*947 = 947/2 units.\\n3. Ellie paints one third of her section: (1/3)*947 = 947/3 units.\\n4. The total red-painted portion is 947/2 + 947/3 = 947*(1/2 + 1/3).\\n5. Compute the sum inside the parentheses: 1/2 + 1/3 = (3/6 + 2/6) = 5/6.\\n6. So, total red-painted length = 947*(5/6) units.\\n7. The fraction of the entire wall painted red is (947*(5/6)) / 1894.\\n8. Notice that 1894 = 947 * 2, so the fraction simplifies to (947*(5/6))/(947*2) = (5/6)/2 = 5/12.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>5/12</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The phrases 'income tax return', 'directed 947 angle', and 'My favorite type of music is indie folk, have you listened to Fleet Foxes?' are irrelevant to the problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let ABC be an equilateral triangle. From the vertex A a ray is drawn into the interior of the triangle so that it meets one of the sides. When the ray meets a side it reflects according to the law of reflection (the angle of incidence equals the angle of reflection, with the directed angle rule that if it arrives with directed angle α it leaves with directed angle 180°−α). After n bounces the ray returns to A without ever hitting either of the other vertices. Find all possible values of n.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "We can solve this problem by the standard unfolding method for billiards in a polygon. In an equilateral triangle (all angles 60°) a reflection in a side is replaced by reflecting the entire triangle so that the ray continues in a straight line. Thus after several bounces the trajectory from A becomes a straight-line segment from the original point A to some copy A′ of A in a triangular tiling of the plane. (Note that the vertices of these reflected copies form a triangular lattice.) The number n of bounces equals the number of sides crossed by this straight segment. In such tiling problems one may show that if one expresses the displacement from A to A′ in an appropriate lattice basis (say, u = side of the triangle and v = side rotated by 60°), then if A′ = m·u + n·v with integers m,n (not both zero) then the total number of edge crossings is\n     N = |m| + |n| + |m+n|.\nMoreover, to avoid the ray hitting any vertex in between (i.e. the segment does not pass through any lattice point other than its endpoints) one must require that the vector (m,n) be primitive in the sense that no non‐trivial lattice point lies on the open segment from 0 to (m,n).\nNote that the two sides leaving A are the sides which meet at A; thus a trivial case such as going from A to an adjacent vertex (which would occur if one of m or n were 0) is excluded.\nThe smallest possible positive values occur when we take m and n both nonzero. For example, choosing m = 1 and n = 1 gives |1| + |1| + |1+1| = 1+1+2 = 4; that is, the ray bounces 4 times before returning to A. Other choices give 6, 8, 10, … etc. In fact one may show that every such primitive lattice vector (with both coefficients nonzero) yields an even number N of bounces with N ≥ 4.\nThus the answer is that the number of bounces n must be even and at least 4; i.e. n = 4, 6, 8, 10, … .",
  "final_answer": "<answer>All even integers n with n ≥ 4; that is, n = 4, 6, 8, …</answer>"
}

