  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Three distinct vertices are randomly selected from the five vertices of a regular pentagon. Let p be the probability that the triangle formed by the chosen vertices is acute. Compute 10p.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Compute the total number of triangles. There are C(5,3)=10 ways to choose 3 vertices from 5.\\nStep 2: Determine the condition for an acute triangle. In a circle (or for vertices of a regular pentagon), a triangle is obtuse if one of the gaps between consecutive vertices (when arranged in cyclic order) corresponds to an arc greater than 180°. For a regular pentagon with vertices equally spaced (each arc 72°), a gap of 3 or more edges (i.e., 216° or more) causes an obtuse angle. Hence, a triangle is acute if and only if no gap is 3 or more.\\nStep 3: Label the vertices 0, 1, 2, 3, 4 in cyclic order. List the triangles and compute the gaps (differences between consecutive vertices, taking wrap-around into account):\\n- {0,1,2}: gaps = 1, 1, 3 → contains gap 3 (obtuse)\\n- {0,1,3}: gaps = 1, 2, 2 → all gaps ≤ 2 (acute)\\n- {0,1,4}: gaps = 1, 3, 1 → gap of 3 (obtuse)\\n- {0,2,3}: gaps = 2, 1, 2 → acute\\n- {0,2,4}: gaps = 2, 2, 1 → acute\\n- {0,3,4}: gaps = 3, 1, 1 → adjacent gap of 3 (obtuse)\\n- {1,2,3}: gaps = 1, 1, 3 → obtuse\\n- {1,2,4}: gaps = 1, 2, 2 → acute\\n- {1,3,4}: gaps = 2, 1, 2 → acute\\n- {2,3,4}: gaps = 1, 1, 3 → obtuse\\nStep 4: Count the acute triangles. They are {0,1,3}, {0,2,3}, {0,2,4}, {1,2,4}, and {1,3,4}, for a total of 5 acute triangles.\\nStep 5: Calculate the probability p = (number of acute triangles)/(total triangles) = 5/10 = 1/2.\\nStep 6: Compute 10p = 10 × (1/2) = 5.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>5</answer>"
}

