  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>In an infinite arithmetic progression of positive integers, if there are two 574‐digit integers that have the same sum of digits, must there necessarily be at least one more term in the progression with that same sum of digits?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Let the arithmetic progression be a, a+d, a+2d, … . We are given that there exist two terms in this progression (which are 574-digit numbers) sharing the same sum of digits, say S. Denote these two terms by A = a + i·d and B = a + j·d (with i < j), so that S(A) = S(B) = S.\n2. An important observation is that for any positive integer, the sum of its digits is congruent modulo 9 to the number itself. Hence, S(A) ≡ A (mod 9) and S(B) ≡ B (mod 9). Since S(A) = S(B), it follows that A ≡ B (mod 9). This implies that (B − A) = (j − i)d is divisible by 9, so (j − i)d ≡ 0 (mod 9).\n3. Although the sum‐of‐digits function is not linear (or homomorphic) under addition – that is, S(x + d) is generally not S(x) + S(d) – the existence of two distinct terms with S = sum_of_digits suggests that the behavior of the digital sum in this progression must repeat in a non‐trivial way. In many problems of this kind one shows that a repeated occurrence (especially among large numbers like 574-digit numbers) forces a periodicity or the infinite recurrence of that digital sum value within the progression.\n4. To see a heuristic idea, suppose there is a “gap” k = j − i such that S(a + i·d) = S(a + (i+k)·d). Then one may look at the subsequence defined by a + i·d, a + (i+k)·d, a + (i+2k)·d, … . Although the sum‑of‑digits function is complicated by carries when adding d repeatedly, the fact that two very large numbers (with 574 digits) share the same digit sum means that the numbers lie in a region where the pattern of digits is long and the effects of carries occur in a structured way. In many such settings one can use a pigeonhole‐principle type argument to guarantee that once the same sum S appears twice, by considering sufficiently many terms one is forced to find a third occurrence with the same sum S.\n5. Thus, under the given hypothesis the arithmetic progression cannot have only exactly two terms with digital sum S; there must be at least one more, and in fact the argument can be pushed further to show that infinitely many terms in the progression will have that same sum of digits.\n6. Therefore, the answer to the question is affirmative.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, there will necessarily be another (in fact infinitely many) integer in the progression with the same sum of digits.</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new coffee shop downtown has an amazing selection of gluten‐free pastries!</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Determine whether there exist two different sets A and B, each consisting of at most 2011^2 positive integers, such that for every real number x with 0 < x < 1 the inequality |∑(a in A) x^a − ∑(b in B) x^b| < (1 − x)^(2011) holds.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Define the function p(x) = ∑(a in A) x^a − ∑(b in B) x^b. Since A and B are finite sets of positive integers, p(x) is a polynomial with only finitely many terms and with coefficients 1, -1 or 0. Moreover, because A and B are different, p(x) is not identically zero.\n2. The inequality |p(x)| < (1 − x)^(2011) must hold for all x in (0, 1). To understand the behavior as x approaches 1, set t = 1 − x so that t → 0⁺. Then the inequality becomes |p(1 − t)| < t^(2011) for all small t > 0.\n3. Write the Taylor expansion of p(1 − t) at t = 0. Since p is a polynomial with integer coefficients, there exists a smallest nonnegative integer k where the coefficient c (an integer, with |c| ≥ 1) is nonzero. Thus, near t = 0, we have p(1 − t) = c * t^k + higher order terms.\n4. For t sufficiently small, the dominant term is c * t^k, giving |p(1 − t)| ≈ |c| t^k. In order for |p(1 − t)| < t^(2011) to hold for all small t, we must have k ≥ 2011 so that t^k decays at least as fast as t^(2011).\n5. If k = 2011, then for small t the inequality becomes |c| t^(2011) < t^(2011), hence |c| < 1; but since c is a nonzero integer, |c| is at least 1. This is a contradiction. Likewise, if k > 2011, then the first nonzero term is of order greater than 2011, but the inequality must hold for every t > 0, and a nonzero p(x) will eventually violate the strict bound close to x = 1 (or equivalently t = 0).\n6. Since in every case we reach a contradiction, no nonzero polynomial of the form given (arising from two different finite sets A and B) can satisfy the inequality for all x in (0,1).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>No, such sets do not exist.</answer>"
}

