  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Given a circle of n > 1 people, Bob places either a black or white hat on each person’s head so that each person sees all hats except his own. All participants must simultaneously guess their own hat color, following a common strategy chosen by Ana. Bob, acting adversarially, assigns the hats after the strategy is fixed. What is the maximum number of correct guesses that Ana can guarantee?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that this is a classic hat guessing puzzle with two hat colors. A well-known strategy uses parity. \nStep 2: The participants agree in advance to designate one person as the ‘parity announcer’. This person counts the number of black hats he sees among the others and then guesses the color that would make the overall number of black hats (including his own, if his guess were correct) even (or odd, if that is the agreed parity). \nStep 3: The remaining n-1 people then use both the hats they see and the parity information implicit in the designated person’s guess to deduce the color of their own hat. \nStep 4: Due to Bob’s adversarial choice, the designated announcer might be forced into an error if his own hat does not match the requirement for the overall parity. However, all the other n-1 people will be correct. \nStep 5: Thus, regardless of Bob’s hat assignment, the strategy guarantees that at least n-1 people will guess correctly.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>n-1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"947\", \"The new coffee shop downtown has a lovely atmosphere.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Consider an airline operating flights between any two capital cities in the European Union. Each flight has a fixed price (the same in both directions) and, from any given city, the flight prices are pairwise distinct. Anna and Bella wish to visit each city exactly once (they need not start from the same city). During her tour, Anna always takes the cheapest flight available from her current city to a city she has not visited yet, while Bella always takes the most expensive available flight. Is it true that Bella’s tour will surely cost at least as much as Anna’s tour?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "We are given a complete graph of cities (since every pair of capital cities is connected by a flight) in which every edge (flight) has a distinct cost from the perspective of its originating city. Although the two travelers might start at different cities and hence have different sets of available edges at each step, the decision rule at every step is local: Anna always picks the minimum‐cost edge from her current city among those going to not-yet-visited cities, while Bella picks the maximum-cost one. For any given city, if we list the available flights (edges) in increasing order then the cheapest is the smallest value and the most expensive is the largest value. Even though in the evolving tours the set of unvisited cities may differ, one may compare the choices made at each step from the same city (if the same city is reached in each tour, or using an appropriate renaming of steps when comparing any two “greedy” selections). On each decision from a specific city, the edge chosen by Bella (the most expensive option among the available flights from that city) is at least as expensive as the edge chosen by Anna (the cheapest among the same set) because, by definition of minimum versus maximum in a set, we get: cheapest edge ≤ most expensive edge. Summing over all steps in the tours (which both consist of the same number of edges – one less than the total number of cities), the sum of the costs in Bella’s tour is at least the sum in Anna’s tour. In other words, no matter the instance or the order of cities visited, Bella’s rule always forces her to choose flights that, on every step, do not cost less than the corresponding flights chosen by Anna, so her total tour cost can never be lower than Anna’s.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, Bella’s tour will always cost at least as much as Anna’s tour.</answer>"
}

