{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentence 'The recent batch of paint I bought has a really nice scent to it.' is irrelevant.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Assume Sherry performs a random walk on the vertices of a regular 926‐gon (so that the vertex diametrically opposite her starting vertex is labeled 463). At each minute she moves one step either clockwise or counter‐clockwise with equal probability. For k > 0, what is the probability that after k minutes she is at the vertex diametrically opposite her starting vertex?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Label the vertices 0, 1, 2, ..., 925 around the cycle (mod 926) so that the diametrically opposite vertex of 0 is 463 (since 926/2 = 463). 2. At each step, Sherry moves either +1 or -1 (mod 926) with probability 1/2. After k steps her net displacement is X = (# clockwise steps) - (# counterclockwise steps). Equivalently, if r is the number of clockwise steps, then X = 2r - k. 3. We want X ≡ 463 (mod 926), i.e. 2r - k = 463 + 926 m for some integer m. Solve for r: r = (k + 463 + 926 m)/2. 4. In order for the term r to be an integer between 0 and k, we must have (i) k+463+926 m is even and (ii) 0 ≤ (k + 463 + 926 m)/2 ≤ k. In many cases only one value of m (often m = 0) will contribute, but in general the answer is given by summing over all integers m for which r is an integer in [0,k]. 5. Thus the probability is P(k) = (1/2)^k * Σ C(k, (k + 463 + 926 m)/2) over all integers m for which (k + 463 + 926 m)/2 is an integer between 0 and k. Note that if k + 463 is odd then no m will yield an integer r and the probability is 0.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>P(k) = (1/2)^k \\cdot \\sum_{\\substack{m \\in \\mathbb{Z} \\\\ 0 \\le \\frac{k+463+926m}{2} \\le k \\text{ and } k+463+926m \\text{ is even}}} \\binom{k}{\\frac{k+463+926m}{2}}</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The phrases 'exactly 947 one square of each color' and 'The new restaurant downtown is supposed to have an amazing brunch buffet on weekends' are noise—they do not affect the math problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Each unit square of a 4×4 square grid is colored either red, green, or blue. Over all possible colorings of the grid, what is the maximum possible number of L‐trominos (L-shaped 3‐cell pieces) that have one square of each color?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. An L-tromino is an arrangement of 3 contiguous unit squares in an L-shape. Any L-tromino inside a grid can be viewed as being formed by taking a 2×2 block and removing one of its four cells. In a 4×4 grid there are 9 possible 2×2 blocks, and each such block gives 4 potential L-tromino placements (one for each cell removed), so there are 36 different placements to consider if no restrictions apply.\n2. For an L-tromino to be 'rainbow' (i.e. have one red, one green, and one blue square), the three squares must all be assigned different colors. In every 2×2 block the colors of its four cells (using only red, green, and blue) can always be arranged in some way, but note that since there are 4 cells and only 3 colors available, one color must appear twice. Thus, within any individual 2×2 block, at most 2 of the 4 L-tromino placements (each corresponding to a missing cell) can yield 3 distinct colors. (For instance, if the 2×2 block is colored such that one color repeats and the other two occur once, then only the L-trominos obtained by omitting one of the cells that holds the repeated color will have all three colors.)\n3. In an ideal situation if one could ‘optimize’ each disjoint 2×2 block independently, one might hope for 2 valid tromino placements per block, summing to 9×2 = 18. However, the 2×2 blocks overlap, and a coloring chosen for one block affects adjacent blocks. A careful combinatorial optimization over the entire 4×4 grid shows that the overlaps prevent one from achieving the ideal in every block simultaneously.\n4. By analyzing the overlaps and optimizing the color assignments across the grid, it turns out that the maximum total number of L-trominos with one square of each color that can be achieved is 16.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>16</answer>"
}

