{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The weather in Paris is particularly lovely during the springtime.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find the number of nonempty families F of subsets of {1, 2, ..., 2014} such that: (a) for any S1, S2 in F, the intersection S1 ∩ S2 is in F; and (b) if S is in F and S ⊆ T ⊆ {1, 2, ..., 2014}, then T is in F.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Any family F satisfying (a) and (b) is in fact a filter in the Boolean lattice of subsets of {1, 2, ..., 2014}. Property (a) shows that F is closed under intersections, and property (b) shows that F is upward closed (i.e. if it contains a set, then it contains all supersets of that set). \n2. In a finite Boolean lattice every filter is principal. This means there exists a unique minimal element m (the intersection of all sets in F) such that F = {T ⊆ {1, 2, ..., 2014} : m ⊆ T}. \n3. Conversely, for any subset m of {1, 2, ..., 2014}, the set F_m = {T ⊆ {1, 2, ..., 2014} : m ⊆ T} satisfies both properties. \n4. Since m can be any subset of {1, 2, ..., 2014} (including the empty set, which gives the full power set), the number of such families F is equal to the number of subsets of {1, 2, ..., 2014}. \n5. The number of subsets of a set with 2014 elements is 2^(2014).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2^(2014)</answer>"
}

