  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Notice that each entry of the matrix is given by i+j, so we can decompose A into two matrices: one that depends only on i and one that depends only on j. Write A₍ᵢⱼ₎ = i + j = f(i) + g(j), where f(i)=i and g(j)=j.\nStep 2: Define two vectors: u = [1, 2, 3, ..., n]ᵀ and v = [1, 1, ..., 1]ᵀ. Then one matrix can be written as u*vᵀ which is of rank 1. Similarly, define w = [1, 1, ..., 1]ᵀ and z = [1, 2, 3, ..., n]ᵀ so that the second matrix is w*zᵀ, again of rank 1.\nStep 3: Therefore, A = u*vᵀ + w*zᵀ is the sum of two rank 1 matrices, so its rank is at most 2.\nStep 4: For n ≥ 2, these two rank 1 matrices are not scalar multiples of each other, so they contribute two independent directions. Hence, the rank of A is exactly 2. (Note: if n = 1, the matrix is 1×1 and its rank is 1.)",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2 (for n ≥ 2; if n = 1 the rank is 1)</answer>"
