  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let f: Q -> Q be a function such that for any x, y in Q, the number f(x+y) - f(x) - f(y) is an integer. Does there exist a constant c such that f(x) - c x is an integer for every rational number x?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Define the function g(x) = f(x) (mod Z), that is, take the fractional part of f(x) in Q/Z. The given condition f(x+y) - f(x) - f(y) in Z implies that g(x+y) = g(x) + g(y) in Q/Z.\\n2. Since g is an additive homomorphism from Q to Q/Z and Q is a divisible group, any such homomorphism is linear. In other words, there exists a rational number a such that g(x) = a x (mod Z) for every x in Q.\\n3. This identity can be rewritten as f(x) ≡ a x (mod Z), meaning that f(x) - a x is an integer for every x in Q.\\n4. Therefore, if we set c = a, we obtain the desired property: f(x) - c x ∈ Z for all x in Q.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, such a constant exists.</answer>"
